00:33:40.450 --> 00:33:48.169
a human and what responsibilities that entails
and also what it means to be like a citizen

00:33:48.169 --> 00:33:49.169
of the earth.

00:33:49.169 --> 00:33:50.169
&gt;&gt;female in audience: Um-hum.

00:33:50.169 --> 00:33:54.730
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: And this is, this
is something that I felt as I was writing

00:33:54.730 --> 00:33:59.279
the book and I've been very, very happy in
feeling like it's been shown out in the conversations

00:33:59.279 --> 00:34:03.730
that I've had since which is that we all already
share the values that would inspire one to

00:34:03.730 --> 00:34:04.730
stop eating --

00:34:04.730 --> 00:34:05.730
&gt;&gt;female in audience: Right.

00:34:05.730 --> 00:34:08.810
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: meat, or to eat less
meat. No one needs to acquire new values.

00:34:08.810 --> 00:34:13.429
You don't need to persuade anybody to-to care
about these things only to act on the care

00:34:13.429 --> 00:34:16.840
that they already have. And so then it's a
question of well, what are the different ways

00:34:16.840 --> 00:34:20.870
that people can act? How can you expand the
action rather than contract it?

00:34:20.870 --> 00:34:26.060
And it might be that holding a sign that says,
"Meat is murder," on a street corner contracts

00:34:26.060 --> 00:34:30.100
people's desire to act, whereas like offering
them flexibility they'll say, "Ah, that might

00:34:30.100 --> 00:34:31.100
feel good. I'll try that."

00:34:31.100 --> 00:34:32.100
&gt;&gt;female voice: [unintelligible]

00:34:32.100 --> 00:34:33.100
&gt;&gt;female in audience: Oh yeah, absolutely.

00:34:33.100 --> 00:34:34.330
Thank you very much.

00:34:34.330 --> 00:34:36.860
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Thank you.

00:34:36.860 --> 00:34:37.860
[pause]

00:34:37.860 --> 00:34:43.100
&gt;&gt;male in audience #1: Hi. Thanks for the
