00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:27.742
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Okay.

00:37:27.742 --> 00:37:32.480
And then the third one was somebody somewhere
must have asked you how do you know plants

00:37:32.480 --> 00:37:33.480
don't feel pain?

00:37:33.480 --> 00:37:35.090
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: How do I know plants
don't feel pain?

00:37:35.090 --> 00:37:37.110
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Hasn't somebody asked
you that question in your --

00:37:37.110 --> 00:37:41.520
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: They usually ask it
in a, in a, in a more annoying form which

00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:43.880
is something like, "But you don't you hear
the carrots crying?"

00:37:43.880 --> 00:37:45.090
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Yeah.

00:37:45.090 --> 00:37:46.090
[laughter]

00:37:46.090 --> 00:37:49.490
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: I don't know that
plants don't feel pain. I don't know that

00:37:49.490 --> 00:37:50.490
you feel pain.

00:37:50.490 --> 00:37:55.440
We make assumptions and our assumptions are
usually based in evidence –

00:37:55.440 --> 00:37:56.440
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Um-hum.

00:37:56.440 --> 00:37:59.810
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: in science so science
gives us many, many reasons to think that

00:37:59.810 --> 00:38:03.490
other human beings experience pain in a way
that's sort of similar to the ways that we

00:38:03.490 --> 00:38:05.350
do.

00:38:05.350 --> 00:38:12.240
And it also gives us reasons to think that
dogs care when you kick them and that a pig

00:38:12.240 --> 00:38:17.740
cares when you kick it and that a cow cares
when you kick it and that a fish on a hook

00:38:17.740 --> 00:38:23.221
that appears to be struggling for its life
and appears to be squirming in something like

00:38:23.221 --> 00:38:26.670
pain is not just giving us false indications.

00:38:26.670 --> 00:38:32.940
That-that chemistry of its brain, the ways
that the-the nerves are organized resemble

00:38:32.940 --> 00:38:38.330
those in humans to such an extent that we
have good reason to think that they are having

00:38:38.330 --> 00:38:42.630
experiences that include suffering or pain
or whatever you wanna call it.

00:38:42.630 --> 00:38:50.640
And we don't have any reason to think that
plants experience pain. But as I said, we'll

00:38:50.640 --> 00:38:56.150
never know so it comes down to what kind of
assumptions you wanna make. And it's better

00:38:56.150 --> 00:39:00.900
to be someone who makes generous assumptions
than someone who's miserly with his assumptions.

00:39:00.900 --> 00:39:05.630
You depend on me to believe you when you slam
your thumb in a car door and say, "Ah, Jesus

00:39:05.630 --> 00:39:10.500
Christ, that fucking hurts." You want me to
say, "Hey, are you okay? Do you need to go

00:39:10.500 --> 00:39:15.700
to the hospital?" Because I could make other
assumptions about you. I could say, "Oh there

00:39:15.700 --> 00:39:19.670
he goes again just showing me all the symptoms;
exhibiting all of the pain behavior --

00:39:19.670 --> 00:39:20.670
[laughter]

00:39:20.670 --> 00:39:22.030
but I know he's not really feeling pain."

00:39:22.030 --> 00:39:26.070
In fact humans are good at doing this. And
have historically been very good about assuming

00:39:26.070 --> 00:39:32.960
that other humans don't feel things in the
same way; humans of different races or sexes.

00:39:32.960 --> 00:39:43.480
So the goal in life is to expand I think our-our
definition of pain not to contract it.

00:39:43.480 --> 00:39:45.030
And if you're proven wrong --

00:39:45.030 --> 00:39:46.030
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Yes.

00:39:46.030 --> 00:39:47.840
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: You know if you're
proven wrong and it turns out the pig actually

00:39:47.840 --> 00:39:52.400
feels nothing, what have you lost? A bunch
of pretty good meals. But if you're proven

00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:56.340
right, then we have something very, very serious
on our hands.

00:39:56.340 --> 00:39:59.840
&gt;&gt;female in audience #2: Hi there. Thank you
so much for coming. I love your-your fiction

00:39:59.840 --> 00:40:04.160
and I read this book and I love your non-fiction.

00:40:04.160 --> 00:40:07.900
It's also preaching to the choir 'cause I'm
an 11 year vegetarian who doesn't wear leather.

00:40:07.900 --> 00:40:14.930
But my question is I learned all these interesting
facts that just further solidified my decisions,

00:40:14.930 --> 00:40:20.250
but I wanted to see if you had any ideas on
how we can take this to the next step and

00:40:20.250 --> 00:40:25.920
impact the food industry, and take all these
facts and make sure that this kind of these

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:31.040
atrocities don't happen 'cause they're not
only what I perceive to be cruel, but they're

00:40:31.040 --> 00:40:32.040
unhealthy for humans.

00:40:32.040 --> 00:40:38.380
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Well, farmers grow
what we ask them to grow not what they want

00:40:38.380 --> 00:40:39.380
to grow.

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:44.260
And if you go to any supermarket now you'll
see cage-free or free range eggs and you wouldn't

00:40:44.260 --> 00:40:49.040
have seen them in any supermarket probably
five years ago. You see it in gas stations

00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:51.540
now. I mean everywhere they have them.

00:40:51.540 --> 00:40:55.630
And it's not because these companies woke
up and said, "It's probably a, like just the

00:40:55.630 --> 00:40:59.490
right thing to do to get them out of these
cages." They did it because it's what people

00:40:59.490 --> 00:41:04.170
asked for. It's the fastest growing sector
in the food industry: cage-free and free range

00:41:04.170 --> 00:41:09.410
eggs. Not in Berkeley and not in Brooklyn,
but in the entire United States.

00:41:09.410 --> 00:41:13.480
It's a food that doesn't taste any better
and isn't any better for us, but people are

00:41:13.480 --> 00:41:17.290
buying because it's just the right thing to
do. No one needs to be persuaded that it's

00:41:17.290 --> 00:41:21.780
wrong to keep an animal that's the size of
a football in a cage about the size of this

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:25.470
book. It's just not right.

00:41:25.470 --> 00:41:29.130
So as people have asked for different things
they've started producing different things.

00:41:29.130 --> 00:41:32.910
So at a certain point I think a tipping point
will be reached in much the same way that

00:41:32.910 --> 00:41:38.030
it has, was reached with smoking. Where we,
there was a period where everyone had access

00:41:38.030 --> 00:41:42.180
to the information and we all knew it but
we just weren't quite acting on it and the

00:41:42.180 --> 00:41:49.270
conversation had to cha, expand and change
in such a way that if just one thing led to

00:41:49.270 --> 00:41:53.430
another and suddenly there was legislation
happening at the same time as the consciousness

00:41:53.430 --> 00:41:54.430
was changing.

00:41:54.430 --> 00:42:00.150
And-and now it's legal to smoke cigarettes.
It will always be legal to eat meat, but I

00:42:00.150 --> 00:42:04.991
do think that in the not too distant future
the question won't be why don't you eat it,

00:42:04.991 --> 00:42:06.260
but why do you eat it?

00:42:06.260 --> 00:42:07.580
&gt;&gt;female in audience: Okay.

00:42:07.580 --> 00:42:08.580
[pause]

00:42:08.580 --> 00:42:12.241
&gt;&gt;female in audience #3: I have a somewhat
similar question to the question that she

00:42:12.241 --> 00:42:19.760
just asked. I feel really lucky that I can,
