00:42:58.150 --> 00:42:59.810
I'm lucky enough to have --

00:42:59.810 --> 00:43:01.340
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Did you say an igloo
or an emu? I didn't hear what you said.

00:43:01.340 --> 00:43:03.570
&gt;&gt;female in audience: Igloo. That I, because
I'm --

00:43:03.570 --> 00:43:04.570
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Igloo?

00:43:04.570 --> 00:43:05.720
&gt;&gt;female in audience: Or like a bubble.

00:43:05.720 --> 00:43:07.030
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Like an Eskimo house?

00:43:07.030 --> 00:43:08.030
[laughter]

00:43:08.030 --> 00:43:10.590
Is that what you're saying? I just , I honestly
can't hear what you're saying.

00:43:10.590 --> 00:43:12.490
&gt;&gt;female in audience: My point is that I'm
lucky enough --

00:43:12.490 --> 00:43:13.490
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Yeah.

00:43:13.490 --> 00:43:15.090
&gt;&gt;female in audience: to be able to make these
purchasing decisions about the food that I

00:43:15.090 --> 00:43:16.090
eat.

00:43:16.090 --> 00:43:17.090
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Right.

00:43:17.090 --> 00:43:19.730
&gt;&gt;female in audience: So I guess my question
is if there were some kind of an app where

00:43:19.730 --> 00:43:27.050
I could say, "Okay, Foster Farms, chicken.
What's the condition of living for that animal

00:43:27.050 --> 00:43:30.240
versus I don't know Petaluma Poultry or something
like that?"

00:43:30.240 --> 00:43:34.070
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: It's very difficult
because these are not individual farms; they're

00:43:34.070 --> 00:43:39.300
farm conglomerates. And even on the best farms
I mean what you would really want is to be

00:43:39.300 --> 00:43:43.690
able to trace an individual animal and to
note was this animal given antibiotics at

00:43:43.690 --> 00:43:48.670
any point in its life. And it's not always
bad to give an animal antibiotics. I mean

00:43:48.670 --> 00:43:52.470
a sick animal should be given antibiotics
and a healthy animal should not.

00:43:52.470 --> 00:43:59.220
We give eight times the amount of antibiotics
to healthy animals as we do to sick people.

00:43:59.220 --> 00:44:02.710
Not only because they've been bred in such
a way that they are destined for illness,

00:44:02.710 --> 00:44:08.730
but because it makes them grow faster. That's
the real reason antibiotics are given to animals.

00:44:08.730 --> 00:44:14.530
So the challenge would not be to identify
which brands are good or bad, but which animals

00:44:14.530 --> 00:44:18.830
are raised under what conditions and there's
just too much information that we can never

00:44:18.830 --> 00:44:19.830
know.

00:44:19.830 --> 00:44:25.280
Was this animal's slaughter botched? That's
a really important thing to most people. Like

00:44:25.280 --> 00:44:31.540
if you found out that the steak you are about
to eat came from a cow that for two and a

00:44:31.540 --> 00:44:35.960
half minutes experienced its own slaughter,
let's just say had like its skin pulled up

00:44:35.960 --> 00:44:40.260
over its head, you wouldn't, you probably
wouldn't wanna eat it, right? I mean most

00:44:40.260 --> 00:44:41.260
people wouldn't.

00:44:41.260 --> 00:44:45.760
So that would be a useful piece of information
to you. But you'll never get that piece of

00:44:45.760 --> 00:44:46.760
information.

00:44:46.760 --> 00:44:52.580
And so what happens is when you eat meat you
make a wager like, "I think this is probably

00:44:52.580 --> 00:44:57.390
good enough," or "I don't think it's good
enough." And we don't have nearly enough information

00:44:57.390 --> 00:45:01.540
to know. I mean Temple Grandin who's the most
important person in the livestock industry

00:45:01.540 --> 00:45:11.440
did an audit of-of cattle processing plants
and found that about 32% of the time during

00:45:11.440 --> 00:45:16.460
her announced audits, her pre-announced audits,
there were deliberate acts of cruelty happening

00:45:16.460 --> 00:45:18.130
on a regular basis.

00:45:18.130 --> 00:45:23.820
And that's a really crazy thing to hear. That
when they knew someone was gonna be there

00:45:23.820 --> 00:45:28.720
watching, about a third of the time they were
not accidental acts of cruelty, but deliberate

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:34.190
acts of cruelty not happening rarely but on
a regular basis. So numbers have improved,

00:45:34.190 --> 00:45:37.020
I should say, since she made that audit.

00:45:37.020 --> 00:45:43.370
But maybe should we think one out of three,
one out of two, everyone has his or her own

00:45:43.370 --> 00:45:48.260
calculus. What I know is when I don't eat
meat I don't get involved with that wager.

00:45:48.260 --> 00:45:50.050
I get it right every time.

00:45:50.050 --> 00:45:54.730
That I don't have to worry about, was this
a farm where they keep the manure in lagoons

00:45:54.730 --> 00:46:01.770
outside and it inevitably runs off into local
waterways and gets sprayed through aerosol

00:46:01.770 --> 00:46:06.620
over neighboring fields, or was this a farm
where they have proper waste management?

00:46:06.620 --> 00:46:13.770
Was this a farm where farm workers are pushed
to such an extent that they become at least

00:46:13.770 --> 00:46:19.850
sloppy and at most sadistic? Or is this a
farm where workers are treated well; get a

00:46:19.850 --> 00:46:24.270
decent wage, are allowed to have some control
over the techniques and do their job thoughtfully

00:46:24.270 --> 00:46:27.460
and respectfully?

00:46:27.460 --> 00:46:30.530
We just can't know all of that stuff and there
is no way that we will ever know.

00:46:30.530 --> 00:46:34.680
Fish are quite different because you're just
looking to see if a species is right or not.

00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:41.190
It's not, by the way, one shouldn't necessarily
feel perfect confidence in just knowing that

00:46:41.190 --> 00:46:48.020
a certain kind of tilapia is okay. It says
nothing about how that specific fish was caught.

00:46:48.020 --> 00:46:50.960
What the buy catch rate was.

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:55.650
Or what the fish itself went through which
might seem like a silly or flakey suggestion

00:46:55.650 --> 00:47:01.660
that I'm making, but we have very, very good
reasons to think that they feel quite a bit

00:47:01.660 --> 00:47:06.310
and perhaps every bit as much as like a chicken
does or maybe even a cow.

00:47:06.310 --> 00:47:11.800
And some people say, "That's regrettable.
I don't care that much." Some people say,

00:47:11.800 --> 00:47:14.000
"I care enough to order something else."

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:22.610
But my only point is you're always going to
be largely ignorant. And that's something

00:47:22.610 --> 00:47:25.990
I'm not comfortable with three times a day
or two times a day or even once a day.

00:47:25.990 --> 00:47:27.060
[pause]

00:47:27.060 --> 00:47:35.490
&gt;&gt;male in audience #2: Hey. Thanks for coming.
I really appreciate it.

00:47:35.490 --> 00:47:42.560
So I'd actually kind of like to make an argument
for factory farming in some cases. I think

00:47:42.560 --> 00:47:49.340
there's, all the cases that you've been talking
about have been very easily demonizable like

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:54.260
beef slaughter, chicken slaughter, hard to
argue with a lot of those cases.

00:47:54.260 --> 00:48:01.430
But what about where the lifestyle of this
animal in the wild is threatened by there

00:48:01.430 --> 00:48:03.850
not being a factory farm situation.

00:48:03.850 --> 00:48:09.990
I'm thinking in particular like, well you
just brought up fish. So where tuna is becoming

00:48:09.990 --> 00:48:14.380
extinct, certain species of salmon are becoming
extinct.

00:48:14.380 --> 00:48:22.630
And without factory farming institutions the
demand is such that the fish farmers or the

00:48:22.630 --> 00:48:30.060
fish-fisherman are driven to want to drive
these-these animals into extinction. So --

00:48:30.060 --> 00:48:33.480
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Alright. So just to
be clear we'll only talk about fish unless

00:48:33.480 --> 00:48:34.680
you can think of an example --

00:48:34.680 --> 00:48:35.760
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Well people keep that
barrier set up --

00:48:35.760 --> 00:48:36.760
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Okay.

00:48:36.760 --> 00:48:37.760
&gt;&gt;maler in audience: and we won't go into
that.

00:48:37.760 --> 00:48:38.760
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: So --

00:48:38.760 --> 00:48:39.760
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Wildlife of cows.

00:48:39.760 --> 00:48:42.950
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Salmon farming was
developed for the reason you're describing

00:48:42.950 --> 00:48:48.160
to take pressure off wild salmon population.
And it's a kind of smart idea. Like if we're

00:48:48.160 --> 00:48:52.380
gonna fish these things into extinction, and
by the way, fisheries scientists now estimate

00:48:52.380 --> 00:48:58.220
that in the year 2048 we will have fished
all wild fish into extinction. All wild fish

00:48:58.220 --> 00:49:01.570
in every ocean; there'll be zero wild fish.

00:49:01.570 --> 00:49:05.000
And if that sounds, they're not saying in
about 50 years or midway into the century;

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:08.420
in 2048. It's based on very precise calculations.

00:49:08.420 --> 00:49:14.680
So fisherman said just out of self interest,
"We need more supply somehow; we can't, there

00:49:14.680 --> 00:49:19.600
will be no business if we use all of these
up." And so salmon farming was developed.

00:49:19.600 --> 00:49:23.380
But it curiously happened which was that as
salmon farming took off the-the pressure on

00:49:23.380 --> 00:49:28.710
wild salmon populations increased rather than
decreased, because eating is habit forming.

00:49:28.710 --> 00:49:35.260
And as there was more supply of salmon there
was a-a demand rose faster than the supply

00:49:35.260 --> 00:49:38.580
because you'd see it on more menus and you
would see someone eating it at a table next

00:49:38.580 --> 00:49:39.580
to you.

00:49:39.580 --> 00:49:44.390
And the way most people eat is not, does not
involve lots of inquiry. Maybe people here

00:49:44.390 --> 00:49:47.830
it does, but most people you see somebody
eating salmon and you think, "That looks pretty

00:49:47.830 --> 00:49:52.460
good. I'll get the salmon." And you don't
say, "Is this farmed or is it wild caught?"

00:49:52.460 --> 00:49:58.060
And this gets to a point that the consumer
can't be responsible for asking that question.

00:49:58.060 --> 00:49:59.060
We are, we are --

00:49:59.060 --> 00:50:00.960
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Except when it tastes
better. Wild typically --

00:50:00.960 --> 00:50:02.570
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: I mean there's a –

00:50:02.570 --> 00:50:03.570
&gt;&gt;male in audience: tastes better.

00:50:03.570 --> 00:50:04.730
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: the question does
it taste infinitely good?

00:50:04.730 --> 00:50:05.730
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Sure.

00:50:05.730 --> 00:50:07.330
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: I mean things can
taste better and better and better but do

00:50:07.330 --> 00:50:10.810
they taste infinitely good and is there anything
that, is there anything that brings us more

00:50:10.810 --> 00:50:14.830
pleasure than the taste of salmon? Most people
would say, "Yes."

00:50:14.830 --> 00:50:23.830
So we don't need all of the choices that we
have. This is like, we don't need the choice

00:50:23.830 --> 00:50:28.700
to buy children's toys that are painted with
lead paint. It's just not a choice we need.

00:50:28.700 --> 00:50:32.420
It doesn't make our lives richer; it doesn't
make us feel more free or in touch with our

00:50:32.420 --> 00:50:33.720
Constitution.

00:50:33.720 --> 00:50:38.100
And we don't need the choice to buy Chilean
Sea Bass. We just don't need it in supermarkets

00:50:38.100 --> 00:50:43.180
or restaurants. We shouldn't have it. And
this is what should happen with seafood is

00:50:43.180 --> 00:50:45.790
certain seafood should just become illegal.

00:50:45.790 --> 00:50:50.850
Foods where it falls upon the consumer's responsibility
to be knowledgeable and make the decisions

00:50:50.850 --> 00:50:54.050
about things that one couldn't conceivably
be expected to.

00:50:54.050 --> 00:50:55.050
[pause]

00:50:55.050 --> 00:50:58.950
&gt;&gt;commentator: We have time for one more question.
[inaudible]

00:50:58.950 --> 00:51:03.290
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Oh, sure. I don't
know exactly, I've never addressed the screen

00:51:03.290 --> 00:51:04.290
before but --

00:51:04.290 --> 00:51:05.290
&gt;&gt;commentator: [inaudible]

00:51:05.290 --> 00:51:07.361
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: How do we know their
actually there?

00:51:07.361 --> 00:51:08.361
[laughter]

00:51:08.361 --> 00:51:11.191
Look they're not responding when I say that.

00:51:11.191 --> 00:51:12.191
[laughter]

00:51:12.191 --> 00:51:15.360
&gt;&gt;commentator: Does anybody have a question
from our [unintelligible] --

00:51:15.360 --> 00:51:17.460
&gt;&gt;male in audience #3: Hi, we're here.

00:51:17.460 --> 00:51:18.750
&gt;&gt;commentator: to prove you exist?

00:51:18.750 --> 00:51:20.780
[pause]

00:51:20.780 --> 00:51:22.120
We have time for one last question.

00:51:22.120 --> 00:51:27.140
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: Well, someone has
one here so we might as well.

00:51:27.140 --> 00:51:28.780
&gt;&gt;commentator: Okay. Last question.

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:32.880
&gt;&gt;male in audience #4: Hi. Thanks very much
for coming.

00:51:32.880 --> 00:51:39.480
If what you said near the beginning during
the introduction is true, then almost everybody,

00:51:39.480 --> 00:51:45.480
at least in the United States, knows at least
some of the reasons why eating meat is the

00:51:45.480 --> 00:51:50.970
end of a chain of causes and effects that
has all sorts of bad consequences.

00:51:50.970 --> 00:51:59.630
And so eating meat is for many people a willful
act of setting aside what they think or what

00:51:59.630 --> 00:52:03.730
they know. And that's an uncomfortable thing
to think about.

00:52:03.730 --> 00:52:11.930
It-it just seems to me that it's-it's pretty
important to-to address how people feel about

00:52:11.930 --> 00:52:16.750
eating meat in addition to how they think
about eating meat. And I-I think this is the

00:52:16.750 --> 00:52:21.180
way people invest their own sense of virtue
and their own sense of personal morality into

00:52:21.180 --> 00:52:25.580
what they do is what leads to questions like:
why are you wearing leather shoes if you're

00:52:25.580 --> 00:52:30.590
a vegetarian? It's this feeling that there-there
are virtue points to be scrabbled over and-and

00:52:30.590 --> 00:52:34.230
that you can't let the other person have all
of them.

00:52:34.230 --> 00:52:40.140
And so I just, I just wanted to get more of
your thoughts on how to make thinking about

00:52:40.140 --> 00:52:46.100
that less uncomfortable, less-less of something
that people want to run away from not because

00:52:46.100 --> 00:52:47.980
of what they think but because of their emotions.

00:52:47.980 --> 00:52:51.520
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Safran Foer: I guess I would just
return to what I said before and-and finding

00:52:51.520 --> 00:52:57.660
a way to make it participatory and inclusionary
rather than exclusionary, rather than who

00:52:57.660 --> 00:53:03.010
is getting it more right than somebody else.

00:53:03.010 --> 00:53:08.820
We all depend on a certain like I don't know
if you call it forgiveness or generosity from

00:53:08.820 --> 00:53:15.810
our friends not to call us out every time
that we fall short, like I don't give as much

00:53:15.810 --> 00:53:23.730
money to charity as I should. I don't volunteer
as much as I should. And yet if-if my friends

00:53:23.730 --> 00:53:27.460
were to point that out I don't think that
I would do those things more. I might even

00:53:27.460 --> 00:53:29.420
do them less.

00:53:29.420 --> 00:53:32.580
But if my friends said, "You know what on-on
Saturday I was thinking about going to this

00:53:32.580 --> 00:53:36.550
like homeless shelter to make some sandwiches.
I've just been bothered, I've just been like

00:53:36.550 --> 00:53:40.090
feeling really guilty by how many homeless
people I've been seeing in the neighborhood

00:53:40.090 --> 00:53:45.400
recently and I thought I would do something."
I would say, "I'll go too." I just would 'cause

00:53:45.400 --> 00:53:49.260
it would be participatory and inclusionary
and I know that the experience would make

00:53:49.260 --> 00:53:50.260
me feel better.

00:53:50.260 --> 00:53:55.480
And so the challenge is to present it in a
way that it is not a deprivation but that

00:53:55.480 --> 00:54:01.000
it is something that gives you more. Where
you end, of course there's, you're gonna remove

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:04.620
certain choices from your life and you're
also gonna remove certain pleasures from your

00:54:04.620 --> 00:54:08.560
life. That-that's something we haven't really
talked about but meat smells good and tastes

00:54:08.560 --> 00:54:14.720
good. It does. I think, I'm glad in your introduction
you said what you did, that you want to have

00:54:14.720 --> 00:54:19.960
as full a palate as you can when performing
your art.

00:54:19.960 --> 00:54:23.390
But we don't have a full palate as it is.
I mean there are foods you would not serve

00:54:23.390 --> 00:54:28.130
ever. You wouldn't serve chimp, for example.

00:54:28.130 --> 00:54:34.130
So humans are very good at saying no to things
we want in the interest of other things we

00:54:34.130 --> 00:54:40.570
want, and saying no to things that we want
a lot more than we want meat.

00:54:40.570 --> 00:54:47.920
So we just have to, I think it's-it's a question
of getting used to it, like acclimating to

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:51.930
a different world. The world 50 years ago
was not this world. We didn't have, there

00:54:51.930 --> 00:54:55.430
wasn't the same urgency in the problem, we
didn't have.

00:54:55.430 --> 00:55:02.030
Also the-the knowledge that we now have entails
a responsibility because like we can't plead

00:55:02.030 --> 00:55:07.550
ignorance like people could have 10 or 20
years ago. And I-I really, I wrote this in

00:55:07.550 --> 00:55:10.691
the book and I believe it that it will be
asked of us what did you do when you learned

00:55:10.691 --> 00:55:17.700
about this. And I would much rather say, "I
withdrew" than, "I forgot about it."

00:55:17.700 --> 00:55:19.130
[pause]

